Define a function to generate threshold versus performance plots

We will use this to generate Figures 1 and 3.

This is based on the threshold_perf() function from the probably package (a part of tidymodels) but expands the capability to allow for the range of metrics we can use to include positive and negative predictive value.

threshold_perf_2 = function (.data, truth, estimate, thresholds = NULL, na_rm = TRUE, 
  ...) 
{
  if (is.null(thresholds)) {
    thresholds <- seq(0.5, 1, length = 21)
  }
  nms <- names(.data)
  obs <- tidyselect::vars_select(nms, !!enquo(truth))
  probs <- tidyselect::vars_select(nms, !!enquo(estimate))
  rs_ch <- dplyr::group_vars(.data)
  rs_ch <- unname(rs_ch)
  obs_sym <- sym(obs)
  probs_sym <- sym(probs)
  if (length(rs_ch) == 0) {
    rs_ch <- NULL
    rs_id <- NULL
  }
  else {
    rs_id <- syms(rs_ch)
  }
  if (length(probs) > 1 | length(obs) > 1) 
    stop("`truth` and `estimate` should only be single columns.", 
      call. = FALSE)
  if (!inherits(.data[[obs]], "factor")) 
    stop("`truth` should be a factor", call. = FALSE)
  if (length(levels(.data[[obs]])) != 2) 
    stop("`truth` should be a 2 level factor", call. = FALSE)
  if (!is.numeric(.data[[probs]])) 
    stop("`estimate` should be numeric", call. = FALSE)
  .data <- dplyr::rename(.data, truth = !!obs_sym, prob = !!probs_sym)
  if (!is.null(rs_id)) {
    .data <- dplyr::select(.data, truth, prob, !!!rs_id)
  }
  else {
    .data <- dplyr::select(.data, truth, prob)
  }
  if (na_rm) {
    .data <- na.omit(.data)
  }
  .data <- .data %>% probably:::expand_preds(threshold = thresholds, 
    inc = c("truth", "prob", rs_ch)) %>% mutate(alt_pred = probably:::recode_data(truth, 
    prob, .threshold))
  if (!is.null(rs_id)) {
    .data <- .data %>% group_by(!!!rs_id, .threshold)
  }
  else {
    .data <- .data %>% group_by(.threshold)
  }
  .data_metrics <- .data %>% two_class(truth, estimate = alt_pred)
  sens_vec <- .data_metrics %>% dplyr::filter(.metric == "sens") %>% 
    dplyr::pull(.estimate)
  dist <- .data_metrics %>% dplyr::filter(.metric == "spec") %>% 
    dplyr::mutate(.metric = "distance", .estimate = (1 - 
      sens_vec)^2 + (1 - .estimate)^2)
  .data_metrics <- dplyr::bind_rows(.data_metrics, dist)
  .data_metrics
}

two_class = function (...){
  mets <- metric_set(sens, spec, j_index, accuracy, bal_accuracy, ppv, npv)
  mets(...)
}

Define a function to generate the calibration curve

We will use this function to generate Figure 2. The cal_plot() function below is a modified version of the function displayed on this GitHub page here (https://darrendahly.github.io/post/homr/). The original function was authored by Darren Dahly, PhD and is partially based on Frank Harrell, PhDs rms package.

  cal_plot <- function(data, pred_var,model_name,...){

    require(tidyverse)
    require(viridis)
    require(gridExtra)

# The calibration plot        
    g1 <- mutate(data, bin = ntile(get(pred_var), 5)) %>% 
          # Bin prediction into 5ths
      group_by(bin) %>%
      mutate(n = n(), # Get ests and CIs
             bin_pred = mean(get(pred_var)), 
             bin_prob = mean(as.numeric(outcome)), 
             se = sqrt((bin_prob * (1 - bin_prob)) / n), 
             ul = bin_prob + 1.96 * se, 
             ll = bin_prob - 1.96 * se) %>%
      ungroup() %>%
    ggplot(aes(x = bin_pred, y = bin_prob, ymin = ll, ymax = ul)) +
      geom_pointrange(size = 0.5, color = "black") +
      scale_y_continuous(limits = c(0, 1), breaks = seq(0, 1, by = 0.1)) +
      scale_x_continuous(limits = c(0, 1), breaks = seq(0, 1, by = 0.1)) +
      geom_abline() + # 45 degree line indicating perfect calibration
      geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = FALSE, linetype = "dashed", 
                  color = "black", formula = y~-1 + x) + 
                  # straight line fit through estimates
      # geom_smooth(aes(x = get(pred_var), y = as.numeric(outcome)), 
      #            color = "red", se = FALSE, method = "loess") + 
                  # loess fit through estimates
      xlab("Predicted Epic Deterioration Index, Rescaled 0 to 1") +
      ylab("Observed Risk") +
      theme_minimal() +
      ggtitle(model_name)

# The distribution plot        
    g2 <- ggplot(data, aes(x = get(pred_var))) +
      geom_histogram(fill = "black", bins = 200) +
      scale_x_continuous(limits = c(0, 1), breaks = seq(0, 1, by = 0.1)) +
      xlab("") +
      ylab("") +
      theme_minimal() +
      easy_remove_y_axis() +
      easy_remove_x_axis() +
      theme_void()

      g2 / g1 + plot_layout(heights = c(1,10))

  }

For patients who experience an adverse outcome, remove all EDI predictions that occur at or after the time of the adverse outcome

epic_di_filter_time =
  inner_join(epic_di, covid_cohort) %>%
  mutate(OUTCOME_TIME = pmin(ICU_STATUS_TIME, VENT_START_TIME, na.rm=TRUE) %>% pmin(ED_OR_FLOOR_TO_ICU_TIME, na.rm=TRUE) %>% pmin(DIED_OR_HOSPICE_TIME,na.rm=TRUE)) %>%
  filter(is.na(OUTCOME_TIME) | SCORE_TIME < OUTCOME_TIME) %>%
  select(1:4, OUTCOME_TIME)
Joining, by = "PAT_ENC_CSN_ID"

Generate a composite outcome for ICU status or vent or ICU transfer

  • For requirement of ICU-level care, we will take the first of: status changed to ICU status OR physically transferred from floor to ICU
  • Exclude actively admitted patients (who have not had an event)
  • Since we only have timestamps for events, we will use the latest timestamp to determine the length of follow-up for actively admitted patients
  • Remove hospice DC from outcomes list, thus:
    • Even though the variable is called DIED_OR_HOSPICE_TIME, it only includes death (because hospice patients have been excluded)
latest_timestamp = 
  covid_cohort %>% 
  summarize_at(vars(HOSP_ED_ROOMED_OR_TRANSFER_TIME,
         ADMIT_TIME, ED_TO_FLOOR_TIME,
         ICU_STATUS_TIME,
         ED_OR_FLOOR_TO_ICU_TIME,
         VENT_START_TIME,
         VENT_FINAL_STOP_TIME,
         DIED_OR_HOSPICE_TIME,
         DC_TIME), . %>% max(na.rm=TRUE)) %>% 
  gather() %>% 
  summarize(value = max(value)) %>%
  pull(value)
  
covid_cohort_study =
  covid_cohort %>%
  mutate(OUTCOME = if_else(!is.na(VENT_START_TIME) | !is.na(ICU_STATUS_TIME) | !is.na(ED_OR_FLOOR_TO_ICU_TIME) | !is.na(DIED_OR_HOSPICE_TIME), 'ICU_OR_VENT_OR_DEATH', 'NO_OUTCOME')) %>% 
  mutate(OUTCOME_TIME = pmin(ICU_STATUS_TIME, VENT_START_TIME, na.rm=TRUE) %>% pmin(ED_OR_FLOOR_TO_ICU_TIME, na.rm=TRUE) %>% pmin(DIED_OR_HOSPICE_TIME,na.rm=TRUE)) %>% 
  filter(ADMIT_LEVEL_OF_CARE != 'ICU') %>% 
  filter(DC_DISP != '16 Hospice/Home' | is.na(DC_DISP)) %>% 
  filter(!is.na(DC_TIME) | !is.na(OUTCOME_TIME))

Using the maximum slope (over the prior 4 and 8 hours), calculate the AUC

Since the score is calculated every 15 minutes (4 times per hour), we multiply 4 and 8 hours by 4 to capture the preceding 4 and 8 hours worth of EDI scores, respectively.

for (i in 4 * c(4, 8)) {
  print(i)
  set.seed(1)
  covid_di_study_scores %>% 
    group_by(PAT_ENC_CSN_ID) %>% 
    mutate(ROLLING_LM = slide(MODEL_SCORE, ~lm(.x ~ row_number(.x)), .before = i)) %>% 
    mutate(INTERCEPT = ROLLING_LM %>% map_dbl(. %>% broom::tidy() %>%
             filter(term == '(Intercept)') %>% 
             pull(estimate))) %>% 
    mutate(SLOPE = ROLLING_LM %>% map_dbl(. %>% broom::tidy() %>%
             filter(term == 'row_number(.x)') %>% 
             {if (nrow(.) == 0) NA_real_ else .$estimate})) %>% 
    summarize(SLOPE = max(SLOPE, na.rm = TRUE), OUTCOME = first(OUTCOME)) %>% 
    filter(SLOPE != -Inf & SLOPE != Inf) %>% 
    mutate(OUTCOME = as.factor(OUTCOME) %>% fct_rev()) %>%  
    pROC::roc(OUTCOME, SLOPE, ci=TRUE, ci.method='bootstrap',
              boot.n = 1000, boot.stratified = FALSE) %>% 
    print()
}

Figure 3: Plot threshold vs performance for patients hospitalized for 48 hours who had not yet experienced the outcome

tp_plot_48h = 
  tp_data_48h %>% 
  filter(!.metric %in% c('distance', 'j_index', 'bal_accuracy', 'accuracy')) %>% 
  mutate(.metric = case_when(.metric == 'accuracy' ~ 'Accuracy',
    .metric == 'npv' ~ 'NPV',
    .metric == 'ppv' ~ 'PPV',
    .metric == 'spec' ~ 'Specificity',
    .metric == 'sens' ~ 'Sensitivity')) %>% 
  mutate(.metric = fct_relevel(.metric, 'Sensitivity', 'Specificity', 'PPV', 'NPV')) %>% 
  mutate(.estimate = .estimate * 100) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = .threshold, y = .estimate)) +
  geom_rect(xmin = 0, ymin = 0, xmax = 37.9, ymax = 100, fill = 'lightgreen', alpha = 1/100) +
  geom_line(size=1) + 
  facet_grid(.metric~.) +
  theme_bw() +
  labs(x = 'Epic Deterioration Index Threshold at 48 Hours', y = 'Value (%)')
